# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: property-testing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:property-testing/graph-property] In graph theory, a **graph property** or **graph invariant** is a property of graphs that depends only on the abstract structure, not on graph representations such as particular labellings or drawings of the graph.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] While graph drawing and graph representation are valid topics in graph theory, in order to focus only on the abstract structure of graphs, a **graph property** is defined to be a property preserved under all possible isomorphisms of a graph.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] In other words, it is a property of the graph itself, not of a specific drawing or representation of the graph.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] Informally, the term "graph invariant" is used for properties expressed quantitatively, while "property" usually refers to descriptive characterizations of graphs.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] For example, the statement "graph does not have vertices of degree 1" is a "property" while "the number of vertices of degree 1 in a graph" is an "invariant".
[src:property-testing/graph-property] More formally, a graph property is a class of graphs with the property that any two isomorphic graphs either both belong to the class, or both do not belong to it.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] Equivalently, a graph property may be formalized using the indicator function of the class, a function from graphs to Boolean values that is true for graphs in the class and false otherwise; again, any two isomorphic graphs must have the same function value as each other.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] A graph invariant or graph parameter may similarly be formalized as a function from graphs to a broader class of values, such as integers, real numbers, sequences of numbers, or polynomials, that again has the same value for any two isomorphic graphs.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] These definitions may be extended from properties to numerical invariants of graphs: a graph invariant is hereditary, monotone, or minor-closed if the function formalizing the invariant forms a monotonic function from the corresponding partial order on graphs to the real numbers.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] In addition, graph properties can be classified according to the type of graph they describe: whether the graph is undirected or directed, whether the property applies to multigraphs, etc.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] Easily computable graph invariants are instrumental for fast recognition of graph isomorphism, or rather non-isomorphism, since for any invariant at all, two graphs with different values cannot (by definition) be isomorphic.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] Two graphs with the same invariants may or may not be isomorphic, however.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] A graph invariant *I*(*G*) is called **complete** if the identity of the invariants *I*(*G*) and *I*(*H*) implies the isomorphism of the graphs *G* and *H*.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] Finding an efficiently computable such invariant (the problem of graph canonization) would imply an easy solution to the challenging graph isomorphism problem.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] However, even polynomial-valued invariants such as the chromatic polynomial are not usually complete.
[src:property-testing/graph-property] The claw graph and the path graph on 4 vertices both have the same chromatic polynomial, for example.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] A **locally testable code** is a type of error-correcting code for which it can be determined if a string is a word in that code by looking at a small (frequently constant) number of bits of the string.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] In some situations, it is useful to know if the data is corrupted without decoding all of it so that appropriate action can be taken in response.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] For example, in communication, if the receiver encounters a corrupted code, it can request the data be re-sent, which could increase the accuracy of said data.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Similarly, in data storage, these codes can allow for damaged data to be recovered and rewritten properly.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] In contrast, locally decodable codes use a small number of bits of the codeword to probabilistically recover the original information.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] The fraction of errors determines how likely it is that the decoder correctly recovers the original bit; however, not all locally decodable codes are locally testable.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Clearly, any valid codeword should be accepted as a codeword, but strings that are not codewords could be only one bit off, which would require many (certainly more than a constant number) probes.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] To account for this, testing failure is only defined if the string is off by at least a set fraction of its bits.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] This implies words of the code must be longer than the input strings by adding some redundancy.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Functions of the form $n=k^{1+\epsilon (k)}$ , where $\epsilon (k)$ is a function tending toward 0.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] This makes n closer to linear as k increases.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] These have both been achieved, even with constant query complexity and a binary alphabet, such as with $n=k^{1+1/(\log k)^{c}}$ for any $c\in (0,1)$ .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] The next nearly linear goal is linear up to a polylogarithmic factor; $n={\text{poly}}(\log k)*k$ .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Nobody has yet to come up with a linearly testable code that satisfies this constraint.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] In November 2021 two preprints have reported the first polynomial-time construction of " $c^{3}$ -LTCs" namely locally testable codes with constant rate r , constant distance $\delta$ and constant locality q .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Locally testable codes have a lot in common with probabilistically checkable proofs (PCPs).
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] This should be apparent from the similarities of their construction.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] In both, we are given q random nonadaptive queries into a large string and if we want to accept, we must with probability 1, and if not, we must accept no more than half the time.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] The major difference is that PCPs are interested in accepting x if there exists a w so that $M^{w}(x)=1$ .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Locally testable codes, on the other hand, accept w if it is part of the code.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Many things can go wrong in assuming a PCP proof encodes a locally testable code.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] For example, the PCP definition says nothing about invalid proofs, only invalid inputs.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Despite this difference, locally testable codes and PCPs are similar enough that frequently to construct one, a prover will construct the other along the way.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] One of the most famous error-correcting codes, the Hadamard code, is a locally testable code.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] A codeword x is encoded in the Hadamard code to be the linear function $f(y)={\sum _{i}{x_{i}y_{i}}}$ (mod 2).
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] This requires listing out the result of this function for every possible y, which requires exponentially more bits than its input.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] To test if a string w is a codeword of the Hadamard code, all we have to do is test if the function it encodes is linear.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] This means simply checking if $w(x)\oplus w(y)=w(x\oplus y)$ for x and y uniformly random vectors (where $\oplus$ denotes bitwise XOR).
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] It is easy to see that for any valid encoding w , this equation is true, as that is the definition of a linear function.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Somewhat harder, however, is showing that a string that is $\delta$ -far from C will have an upper bound on its error in terms of $\delta$ .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] One bound is found by the direct approach of approximating the chances of exactly one of the three probes yielding an incorrect result.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Let A, B, and C be the events of $w(x)$ , $w(y)$ , and $w(x\oplus y)$ being incorrect.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Let E be the event of exactly one of these occurring.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] For any given $\delta$ , this only has a constant chance of false positives, so we can simply check a constant number of times to get the probability below 1/2.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] The Long code is another code with very large blowup which is close to locally testable.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Given an input $0\leq i\leq 2^{k}$ (note, this takes k bits to represent), the function that returns the $i^{th}$ bit of the input, $f_{i}(x)=x_{i}$ , is evaluated on all possible $2^{k}$ -bit inputs $0\leq x\leq 2^{2^{k}}$ , and the codeword is the concatenation of these (of length $n=2^{2^{k}}$ ).
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] The way to locally test this with some errors is to pick a uniformly random input x and set $y=x$ , but with a small chance of flipping each bit, $\mu >0$ .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Accept a function f as a codeword if $f(x)=f(y)$ .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] If f is a codeword, this will accept f as long as $x_{i}$ was unchanged, which happens with probability $1-\mu$ .
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] This violates the requirement that codewords are always accepted, but may be good enough for some needs.
[src:property-testing/locally-testable-code] Other locally testable codes include Reed-Muller codes (see locally decodable codes for a decoding algorithm), Reed-Solomon codes, and the short code.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The PCP theorem is the cornerstone of the theory of computational hardness of approximation, which investigates the inherent difficulty in designing efficient approximation algorithms for various optimization problems.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] It has been described by Ingo Wegener as "the most important result in complexity theory since Cook's theorem" and by Oded Goldreich as "a culmination of a sequence of impressive works […] rich in innovative ideas".
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The variable n is the length in bits of the description of a problem instance.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] Note further that the verification algorithm is *non-adaptive*: the choice of bits of the proof to check depend only on the random bits and the description of the problem instance, not the actual bits of the proof.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] An alternative formulation of the PCP theorem states that the maximum fraction of satisfiable constraints of a certain constraint satisfaction problem is NP-hard to approximate within some constant factor.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] where $\Phi$ is a constraint satisfaction problem (CSP) over a Boolean alphabet with at most q variables per constraint.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The connection to the class ${\mathsf {PCP}}$ mentioned above can be seen by noticing that checking a constant number of bits q in a proof can be seen as evaluating a constraint in q Boolean variables on those bits of the proof.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] Since the verification algorithm uses $O(\log n)$ bits of randomness, it can be represented as a CSP as described above with $\operatorname {poly} (n)$ constraints.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] Therefore, an algorithm for the promise problem would be able to solve the underlying NP problem, and hence the promise problem must be NP-hard.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] This can be done by reducing the problem of approximating a solution to such problems to a promise problem of the above form.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] These results are sometimes also called PCP theorems because they can be viewed as probabilistically checkable proofs for NP with some additional structure.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] A proof of a weaker result, ⁠ ${\mathsf {NP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {PCP}}[n^{3},1]$ ⁠ is given in one of the lectures of Dexter Kozen.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The PCP theorem is the culmination of a long line of work on interactive proofs and probabilistically checkable proofs.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The first theorem relating standard proofs and probabilistically checkable proofs is the statement that ${\mathsf {NEXP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {PCP}}[\operatorname {poly} (n),\operatorname {poly} (n)]$ , proved by Babai, Fortnow & Lund (1990).
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The notation ${\mathsf {PCP}}_{c(n),s(n)}[r(n),q(n)]$ is explained at probabilistically checkable proof.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The notation is that of a function that returns a certain complexity class.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The name of this theorem (the "PCP theorem") probably comes either from **"PCP"** meaning "probabilistically checkable proof", or from the notation mentioned above (or both).
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] Subsequently, the methods used in this work were extended by Babai, Lance Fortnow, Levin, and Szegedy in 1991 (Babai et al.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] 1991), Feige, Goldwasser, Lund, Safra, and Szegedy (1991), and Arora and Safra in 1992 (Arora & Safra 1992) to yield a proof of the PCP theorem by Arora, Lund, Motwani, Sudan, and Szegedy in 1998 (Arora et al.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The 2001 Gödel Prize was awarded to Sanjeev Arora, Uriel Feige, Shafi Goldwasser, Carsten Lund, László Lovász, Rajeev Motwani, Shmuel Safra, Madhu Sudan, and Mario Szegedy for work on the PCP theorem and its connection to hardness of approximation.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] In 2005 Irit Dinur discovered a significantly simpler proof of the PCP theorem, using expander graphs.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] She received the 2019 Gödel Prize for this.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] A version of the PCP theorem for quantum nonlocal games would state that it is computationally hard to approximate the quantum value of a quantum nonlocal game.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] In 2012, Thomas Vidick and Tsuyoshi Ito published a result that showed a "strong limitation on the ability of entangled provers to collude in a multiplayer game".
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] This could be a step toward proving the quantum analogue of the PCP theorem, since when the result was reported in the media, professor Dorit Aharonov called it "the quantum analogue of an earlier paper on multiprover interactive proofs" that "basically led to the PCP theorem".
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] In 2018, Thomas Vidick and Anand Natarajan proved a games variant of quantum PCP theorem under randomized reduction.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] It states that ${\mathsf {QMA}}\subseteq {\mathsf {MIP}}^{*}[\log n,1,{\tfrac {1}{2}}]$ , where ${\mathsf {MIP}}^{*}[f(n),c,s]$ is a complexity class of multi-prover quantum interactive proofs systems with $f(n)$ -bit classical communications, and the completeness is c and the soundness is s .
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] A version of the PCP theorem for quantum local Hamiltonians would state that it is computationally hard to approximate the ground energy of a quantum local Hamiltonian.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The work of Natarajan and Vidick also showed that a quantum Hamiltonian version of the PCP theorem, namely the existence of local Hamiltonian problem with constant promise gap $c-s$ which are QMA-hard, implies a quantum nonlocal games version of the PCP theorem.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The NLTS conjecture was an unresolved obstacle and precursor to a quantum Hamiltonian analog of the PCP theorem.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] The conjecture was proven in 2022 by Anurag Anshu, Nikolas Breuckmann, and Chinmay Nirkhe using a construction of a Hamiltonian based on quantum CSS codes.
[src:property-testing/pcp-theorem] However, the ground states of such Hamiltonians are given explicitly by the code states of the corresponding CSS code, and thus are not computationally hard enough for a general proof of a quantum PCP theorem.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] A *property testing algorithm* for a decision problem is an algorithm whose query complexity (the number of queries made to its input) is much smaller than the instance size of the problem.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Property testing algorithms are central to the definition of probabilistically checkable proofs, as a probabilistically checkable proof is essentially a proof that can be verified by a property testing algorithm.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Here, "x is ε-far from L" means that the Hamming distance between x and any string in L is at least *ε* |*x*|.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] A property testing algorithm is said to have *one-sided error* if it satisfies the stronger condition that the accepting probability for instances *x* ∈ *L* is 1 instead of 2/3.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] A property testing algorithm is said be *non-adaptive* if it performs all its queries before it "observes" any answers to previous queries.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Such an algorithm can be viewed as operating in the following manner.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Before looking at the input, using its internal randomness, the algorithm decides which symbols of the input are to be queried.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Next, the algorithm observes these symbols.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Finally, without making any additional queries (but possibly using its randomness), the algorithm decides whether to accept or reject the input.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The main efficiency parameter of a property testing algorithm is its query complexity, which is the maximum number of input symbols inspected over all inputs of a given length (and all random choices made by the algorithm).
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Computer scientists are interested in designing algorithms whose query complexity is as small as possible.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In many cases, the running time of property testing algorithms is sublinear in the instance length.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Typically, the goal is first to make the query complexity as small as possible as a function of the instance size n, and then study the dependency on the proximity parameter ε.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Unlike other complexity-theoretic settings, the asymptotic query complexity of property testing algorithms is affected dramatically by the representation of instances.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] For example, when *ε* = 0.01, the problem of testing bipartiteness of *dense graphs* (which are represented by their adjacency matrix) admits an algorithm of constant query complexity.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In contrast, sparse graphs on n vertices (which are represented by their adjacency list) require property testing algorithms of query complexity Ω(*n*1/2).
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The query complexity of property testing algorithms grows as the proximity parameter ε becomes smaller for all non-trivial properties.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] This dependence on ε is necessary, as a change of fewer than ε symbols in the input cannot be detected with constant probability using fewer than *O*(1/*ε*) queries.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Many interesting properties of dense graphs can be tested using query complexity that depends only on ε and not on the graph size n.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] However, the query complexity can grow enormously fast as a function of ε.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] For example, for a long time, the best known algorithm for testing whether a graph does not contain any triangle had a query complexity which is a tower function of poly(1/*ε*), and only in 2010 was this improved to a tower function of log(1/*ε*).
[src:property-testing/property-testing] One of the reasons for this enormous growth in bounds is that many of the positive results for property testing of graphs are established using the Szemerédi regularity lemma, which also has tower-type bounds in its conclusions.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The connection of property testing to the Szemerédi regularity lemma and related graph removal lemmas is elaborated on below.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] For a graph G with n vertices, the notion of distance we will use is the *edit distance*.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] That is, we say that the distance between two graphs is the smallest ε such that one can add and/or delete *εn*2 edges and get from the first graph to the second.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Under a reasonable representation of graphs, this is equivalent to the earlier *Hamming distance* definition (up to possibly a change of constants).
[src:property-testing/property-testing] To make precise the general notions of property testing in the context of graphs, we say a tester for graph property P should distinguish with at least two-thirds probability between the cases of G satisfying P and the cases where G is ε-far in edit distance from satisfying P.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The tester can access some oracle to query whether a pair of vertices has an edge between them in G or not.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The *query complexity* is the number of such oracle queries.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Say the tester has *one-sided error* if it has false positives and not false negatives, i.e. if G satisfies P, the tester always outputs the correct answer.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] We can only differentiate between graphs that satisfy P versus those far from P, as opposed to satisfying versus not satisfying P.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In the latter case, consider two graphs: G satisfying P and H not satisfying P by changing only a few edges.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] One example is testing triangle-freeness with *H* a graph with exactly one triangle and G having one of these edges removed.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Then, the tester cannot tell them apart unless it queries every edge, which it cannot do.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The field of graph property testing was first introduced by Goldreich, Goldwasser, and Ron.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In their seminal paper published in 1998, an abstract graph partition problem is analyzed and some testers provided.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] These include as special cases several important graph properties like bipartiteness, *k*-colorability, having a large clique, and having a large cut.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In particular, the *natural* algorithms that sample a subgraph and check whether it satisfy the property are all correct, albeit with perhaps-suboptimal query complexities.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] A graph property is *hereditary* if it is preserved under deletion of vertices, or equivalently, if it is preserved under taking induced subgraphs.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] A few important hereditary properties are *H*-freeness (for some graph *H*), k-colorability, and planarity.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Every hereditary graph property is testable with one-sided error.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The proof relies on a version of the **graph removal lemma** for infinite families of induced subgraphs.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The query complexity using this regularity approach is large due to the tower function bound in the **Szemerédi regularity lemma**.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Informally, an *oblivious tester* is oblivious to the size of the input.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] For a graph property P, it is an algorithm that takes as input a parameter ε and graph G, and then runs as a property testing algorithm on G for the property P with proximity parameter ε that makes exactly *q*(*ε*) queries to G.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Crucially, the number of queries an oblivious tester makes is a constant dependent only on ε and not the size of the input graph G.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In complete analogy with property testing algorithms, we can talk about oblivious testers with one-sided error.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] We can contrive some graph properties for which a tester must access the number of vertices.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In this case, the tester cannot even differentiate which property (bipartiteness or perfectness) to test unless it knows the number of vertices.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] There are many examples of such unnatural properties.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In fact, the characterization of graph properties testable by an oblivious tester with one-sided error leads to a class of natural properties.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Trivially, hereditary properties are also semi-hereditary.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] This characterization partially answers the converse to the other Alon & Shapira theorem above: the properties that are easy to test properties (having oblivious testers with one-sided error) are almost hereditary.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In this section, we will give some *natural* oblivious testing algorithms with one-sided error for triangle-freeness, bipartiteness, and k-colorability.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] They are natural in the sense that we follow the natural idea of randomly sampling some subset X of vertices of *G* and checking whether the graph property holds on the subgraph spanned by *X* by brute-force search.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] We have one-sided error since these properties are actually hereditary: if *G* satisfy the property, so must the induced subgraph spanned by *X*, so our tester always accepts.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] For triangle-freeness, the tester is an application of the **triangle removal lemma**.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] In particular, it tells us that if graph *G* is ε-far from being triangle-free, then there is a (computable) constant *δ* = *δ*(*ε*) so that G has at least *δn*3 triangles.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] For bipartiteness and k-colorability, let δ be the desired upper bound on error probability for the following testers.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] Note that query complexity should not be confused with running time.
[src:property-testing/property-testing] The latter is often exponential (as is the case of both) due to a lack of polynomial time decision algorithm to test the property on the induced subgraph.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] A **randomized algorithm** is an algorithm that employs a degree of randomness as part of its logic or procedure.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In some cases, probabilistic algorithms are the only practical means of solving a problem.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] As a motivating example, consider the problem of finding an ‘*a*’ in an array of *n* elements.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] We give two versions of the algorithm, one Las Vegas algorithm and one Monte Carlo algorithm.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm succeeds with probability 1.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Since it is constant, the expected run time over many calls is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] If an ‘*a*’ is found, the algorithm succeeds, else the algorithm fails.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm does not guarantee success, but the run time is bounded.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The number of iterations is always less than or equal to k.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Taking k to be constant the run time (expected and absolute) is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are particularly useful when faced with a malicious "adversary" or attacker who deliberately tries to feed a bad input to the algorithm (see worst-case complexity and competitive analysis (online algorithm)) such as in the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] It is for this reason that randomness is ubiquitous in cryptography.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In cryptographic applications, pseudo-random numbers cannot be used, since the adversary can predict them, making the algorithm effectively deterministic.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, either a source of truly random numbers or a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator is required.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Another area in which randomness is inherent is quantum computing.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In the example above, the Las Vegas algorithm always outputs the correct answer, but its running time is a random variable.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The Monte Carlo algorithm (related to the Monte Carlo method for simulation) is guaranteed to complete in an amount of time that can be bounded by a function the input size and its parameter *k*, but allows a *small probability of error*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Observe that any Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm (via Markov's inequality), by having it output an arbitrary, possibly incorrect answer if it fails to complete within a specified time.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Conversely, if an efficient verification procedure exists to check whether an answer is correct, then a Monte Carlo algorithm can be converted into a Las Vegas algorithm by running the Monte Carlo algorithm repeatedly till a correct answer is obtained.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Computational complexity theory models randomized algorithms as *probabilistic Turing machines*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Both Las Vegas and Monte Carlo algorithms are considered, and several complexity classes are studied.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Problem classes having (possibly nonterminating) algorithms with polynomial time average case running time whose output is always correct are said to be in ZPP.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The class of problems for which both YES and NO-instances are allowed to be identified with some error is called BPP.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] This class acts as the randomized equivalent of P, i.e.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] BPP represents the class of efficient randomized algorithms.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort was discovered by Tony Hoare in 1959, and subsequently published in 1961.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, Hoare published the quickselect algorithm, which finds the median element of a list in linear expected time.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] It remained open until 1973 whether a deterministic linear-time algorithm existed.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In 1917, Henry Cabourn Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Elwyn Berlekamp introduced a randomized algorithm for efficiently computing the roots of a polynomial over a finite field.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Solovay and Volker Strassen discovered a polynomial-time randomized primality test (i.e., determining the primality of a number).
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Rabin demonstrated that the 1976 Miller's primality test could also be turned into a polynomial-time randomized algorithm.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] At that time, no provably polynomial-time deterministic algorithms for primality testing were known.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] One of the earliest randomized data structures is the hash table, which was introduced in 1953 by Hans Peter Luhn at IBM.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Luhn's hash table used chaining to resolve collisions and was also one of the first applications of linked lists.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Subsequently, in 1954, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research introduced linear probing, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea in 1957.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In 1962, Donald Knuth performed the first correct analysis of linear probing, although the memorandum containing his analysis was not published until much later.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Early works on hash tables either assumed access to a fully random hash function or assumed that the keys themselves were random.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In 1979, Carter and Wegman introduced universal hash functions, which they showed could be used to implement chained hash tables with constant expected time per operation.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Early work on randomized data structures also extended beyond hash tables.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Burton Howard Bloom introduced an approximate-membership data structure known as the Bloom filter.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Aragon introduced a randomized balanced search tree known as the treap.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, William Pugh introduced another randomized search tree known as the skip list.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Prior to the popularization of randomized algorithms in computer science, Paul Erdős popularized the use of randomized constructions as a mathematical technique for establishing the existence of mathematical objects.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] This technique has become known as the probabilistic method.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Erdős gave his first application of the probabilistic method in 1947, when he used a simple randomized construction to establish the existence of Ramsey graphs.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] He famously used a more sophisticated randomized algorithm in 1959 to establish the existence of graphs with high girth and chromatic number.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort is a familiar, commonly used algorithm in which randomness can be useful.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Many deterministic versions of this algorithm require *O*(*n*2) time to sort *n* numbers for some well-defined class of degenerate inputs (such as an already sorted array), with the specific class of inputs that generate this behavior defined by the protocol for pivot selection.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] However, if the algorithm selects pivot elements uniformly at random, it has a provably high probability of finishing in *O*(*n* log *n*) time regardless of the characteristics of the input.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In computational geometry, a standard technique to build a structure like a convex hull or Delaunay triangulation is to randomly permute the input points and then insert them one by one into the existing structure.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The randomization ensures that the expected number of changes to the structure caused by an insertion is small, and so the expected running time of the algorithm can be bounded from above.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] This technique is known as randomized incremental construction.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Recall that the contraction of two nodes, *u* and *v*, in a (multi-)graph yields a new node *u* ' with edges that are the union of the edges incident on either *u* or *v*, except from any edge(s) connecting *u* and *v*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Figure 1 gives an example of contraction of vertex *A* and *B*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] After contraction, the resulting graph may have parallel edges, but contains no self loops.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] In each execution of the outer loop, the algorithm repeats the inner loop until only 2 nodes remain, the corresponding cut is obtained.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The run time of one execution is $O(n)$ , and *n* denotes the number of vertices.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] After *m* times executions of the outer loop, we output the minimum cut among all the results.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The figure 2 gives an example of one execution of the algorithm.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] After execution, we get a cut of size 3.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] If *G* is not connected, then *G* can be partitioned into *L* and *R* without any edge between them.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] So the min cut in a disconnected graph is 0.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Initially, *u*,*v* are distinct vertices.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] *As long as we pick an edge ⁠ $f\neq e$ ⁠, u and v do not get merged.* Thus, at the end of the algorithm, we have two compound nodes covering the entire graph, one consisting of the vertices of *L* and the other consisting of the vertices of *R*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] As in figure 2, the size of min cut is 1, and *C* = {(*A*,*B*)}.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] If we don't select (*A*,*B*) for contraction, we can get the min cut.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Because the min cut is *k*, every vertex *v* must satisfy degree(*v*) ≥ *k*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, the sum of the degree is at least *pk*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] But it is well known that the sum of vertex degrees equals 2|*E*|.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the algorithm succeeds is 1 − the probability that all attempts fail.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] By lemma 1, the probability that *C**i* = *C* is the probability that no edge of *C* is selected during iteration *i*.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Consider the inner loop and let *G**j* denote the graph after *j* edge contractions, where *j* ∈ {0, 1, …, *n* − 3}.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] We use the chain rule of conditional possibilities.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the edge chosen at iteration *j* is not in *C*, given that no edge of *C* has been chosen before, is $1-{\frac {k}{|E(G_{j})|}}$ .
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Note that *G**j* still has min cut of size *k*, so by Lemma 2, it still has at least ${\frac {(n-j)k}{2}}$ edges.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Thus the probability that the algorithm succeeds is at least $1-\left(1-{\frac {2}{n(n-1)}}\right)^{m}$ .
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] The algorithm finds the min cut with probability $1-{\frac {1}{n}}$ , in time $O(mn)=O(n^{3}\log n)$ .
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Randomness can be viewed as a resource, like space and time.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] Derandomization is then the process of *removing* randomness (or using as little of it as possible).
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] It is not currently known if all algorithms can be derandomized without significantly increasing their running time.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] For instance, in computational complexity, it is unknown whether P = BPP, i.e., we do not know whether we can take an arbitrary randomized algorithm that runs in polynomial time with a small error probability and derandomize it to run in polynomial time without using randomness.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] When the model of computation is restricted to Turing machines, it is currently an open question whether the ability to make random choices allows some problems to be solved in polynomial time that cannot be solved in polynomial time without this ability; this is the question of whether P = BPP.
[src:property-testing/randomized-algorithm] However, in other contexts, there are specific examples of problems where randomization yields strict improvements.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] In linear algebra, a **sublinear** function (or functional as is more often used in functional analysis), also called a **quasi-seminorm**, on a vector space is a real-valued function with some of the properties of a seminorm.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] Unlike seminorms, a sublinear function does not have to be nonnegative-valued and also does not have to be absolutely homogeneous.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] Seminorms are themselves abstractions of the more well known notion of norms, where a seminorm has all the defining properties of a norm *except* that it is not required to map non-zero vectors to non-zero values.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] In functional analysis the name **Banach functional** is sometimes used, reflecting that they are most commonly used when applying a general formulation of the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] The notion of a sublinear function was introduced by Stefan Banach when he proved the Hahn-Banach theorem.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] A function $p:X\to \mathbb {R}$ is called *positive* or *nonnegative* if $p(x)\geq 0$ for all $x\in X,$ although some authors define *positive* to instead mean that $p(x)\neq 0$ whenever $x\neq 0;$ these definitions are not equivalent.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] It is a *symmetric function* if $p(-x)=p(x)$ for all $x\in X.$ Every subadditive symmetric function is necessarily nonnegative.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] A sublinear function on a real vector space is symmetric if and only if it is a seminorm.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] The set of all sublinear functions on $X,$ denoted by $X^{\#},$ can be partially ordered by declaring $p\leq q$ if and only if $p(x)\leq q(x)$ for all $x\in X.$ A sublinear function is called **minimal** if it is a minimal element of $X^{\#}$ under this order.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] A sublinear function is minimal if and only if it is a real linear functional.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] Every norm, seminorm, and real linear functional is a sublinear function.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] A function $p\colon X\to \mathbb {R}$ which is subadditive, convex, and satisfies $p(0)\leq 0$ is also positively homogeneous (the latter condition $p(0)\leq 0$ is necessary as the example of $p(x)={\sqrt {x^{2}+1}}$ on $X=\mathbb {R}$ shows).
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] If p is positively homogeneous, it is convex if and only if it is subadditive.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] Therefore, assuming $p(0)\leq 0$ , any two properties among subadditivity, convexity, and positive homogeneity implies the third.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] If X is a real TVS, f is a linear functional on $X,$ and p is a continuous sublinear function on $X,$ then $f\leq p$ on X implies that f is continuous.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] Let V be an open convex subset of $X.$ If $0\in V$ then let $z:=0$ and otherwise let $z\in V$ be arbitrary.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] Let $p:X\to [0,\infty )$ be the Minkowski functional of $V-z,$ which is a continuous sublinear function on X since $V-z$ is convex, absorbing, and open ( p however is not necessarily a seminorm since V was not assumed to be balanced).
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] The concept can be extended to operators that are homogeneous and subadditive.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] This requires only that the codomain be, say, an ordered vector space to make sense of the conditions.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] In computer science, a function $f:\mathbb {Z} ^{+}\to \mathbb {R}$ is called **sublinear** if $\lim _{n\to \infty }{\frac {f(n)}{n}}=0,$ or $f(n)\in o(n)$ in asymptotic notation (notice the small o ).
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] Formally, $f(n)\in o(n)$ if and only if, for any given $c>0,$ there exists an N such that $f(n)<cn$ for $n\geq N.$ That is, f grows slower than any linear function.
[src:property-testing/sublinear-function] The two meanings should not be confused: while a Banach functional is convex, almost the opposite is true for functions of sublinear growth: every function $f(n)\in o(n)$ can be upper-bounded by a concave function of sublinear growth.
